# Convex Patterns & Best Practices

## Function Syntax

Always use the **new function syntax** with `args`, `handler`, and optionally `returns` as object properties:

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD: New syntax
export const getBook = query({
  args: { id: v.id('books') },
  handler: async (context, args) => {
    return await context.db.get(args.id)
  },
})

// ❌ BAD: Old syntax
export const getBook = query(async (context, args) => {
  return await context.db.get(args.id)
})
```

## Validators

- **Always specify `args` validator** - every function must validate its arguments
- **Always specify `returns` validator** when returning data (use `v.null()` if returning nothing)
- Use appropriate validators: `v.string()`, `v.number()`, `v.id('tableName')`, `v.array(...)`, `v.optional(...)`, `v.union(...)`, `v.object({...})`

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD: Explicit validators
export const create = mutation({
  args: {
    title: v.string(),
    authors: v.array(v.string()),
    isbn: v.optional(v.string()),
  },
  returns: v.id('books'),
  handler: async (context, args) => {
    return await context.db.insert('books', args)
  },
})

// ❌ BAD: Missing validators
export const create = mutation({
  handler: async (context, args: any) => {
    return await context.db.insert('books', args)
  },
})
```

## Function Types

### Public Functions (exposed to clients)

- `query` - Read-only, reactive, can be called from client
- `mutation` - Write operations, can be called from client
- `action` - External calls, async operations, can be called from client

### Internal Functions (only callable from other Convex functions)

- `internalQuery` - Read-only, called via `context.runQuery()`
- `internalMutation` - Write operations, called via `context.runMutation()`
- `internalAction` - External calls, called via `context.runAction()`

**Rule**: If a function is only used internally (e.g., called from actions or other mutations), use `internal*` variants.

## Database Queries

### Prefer Indexes Over Filters

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD: Using index
const book = await context.db
  .query('books')
  .withIndex('by_asin', (q) => q.eq('asin', args.asin))
  .unique()

// ❌ BAD: Using filter (slower)
const book = await context.db
  .query('books')
  .filter((q) => q.eq(q.field('asin'), args.asin))
  .unique()
```

### Pagination

Use `paginate()` with `paginationOptsValidator` for large result sets:

```typescript
import { paginationOptsValidator } from 'convex/server'

export const listPaginated = query({
  args: {
    paginationOpts: paginationOptsValidator,
  },
  handler: async (context, args) => {
    return await context.db.query('books').order('desc').paginate(args.paginationOpts)
  },
})
```

## Actions

### Node.js Built-ins

If using Node.js built-ins (like `fs`, `http`, `crypto`), add `"use node";` at the top:

```typescript
'use node'

import { action } from '../_generated/server'
import { v } from 'convex/values'

export const fetchExternalData = action({
  args: { url: v.string() },
  handler: async (context, args) => {
    // Can use Node.js built-ins here
  },
})
```

### Don't Use context.db in Actions

Actions cannot directly access the database. Use `context.runQuery()` or `context.runMutation()`:

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD: Using runMutation
export const crawlBook = action({
  args: { url: v.string() },
  handler: async (context, args) => {
    const bookId = await context.runMutation(internal.books.create, {
      title: '...',
    })
  },
})

// ❌ BAD: Direct db access in action
export const crawlBook = action({
  handler: async (context, args) => {
    const bookId = await context.db.insert('books', {...}) // ERROR!
  },
})
```

### Scheduling Work

Use `context.scheduler.runAfter()` or `context.scheduler.runAt()` to chain async operations:

```typescript
export const crawlBook = action({
  handler: async (context, args) => {
    // Schedule follow-up work
    await context.scheduler.runAfter(0, internal.scraping.downloadCover, {
      bookId,
      imageUrl: args.coverUrl,
    })
  },
})
```

## Schema & Indexes

- Define indexes in `schema.ts` using `.index('indexName', ['field1', 'field2'])`
- Use descriptive index names: `by_asin`, `by_status`, `by_author_id`
- Indexes enable efficient queries - always use them for filtered queries

## File Storage

- Use `context.storage.getUrl(storageId)` to get public URLs for stored files
- Store file IDs in your schema: `coverStorageId: v.optional(v.id('_storage'))`
- Always check if storageId exists before calling `getUrl()`

## Error Handling

- Throw errors for exceptional cases
- Use `v.optional()` for fields that might not exist
- Return `null` from queries when entity not found (don't throw)

```typescript
export const get = query({
  args: { id: v.id('books') },
  handler: async (context, args) => {
    const book = await context.db.get(args.id)
    if (!book) return null // ✅ Return null, don't throw
    return book
  },
})
```

## Type Safety

- Import types from `../_generated/dataModel` for table IDs: `Id<'books'>`
- Import `internal` from `../_generated/api` for internal function references
- Import `api` from `../_generated/api` for public function references

### Never Manually Define Types from Convex Queries

**Always use `FunctionReturnType` to extract types from Convex queries/mutations instead of manually defining types.** This ensures types stay in sync with the actual Convex function return values.

```typescript
import type { FunctionReturnType } from 'convex/server'
import { api } from '@/convex/_generated/api'

// ✅ GOOD: Extract type from query return value (single value)
type Book = NonNullable<FunctionReturnType<typeof api.books.queries.getBySlugOrId>>

// ✅ GOOD: For array returns, extract element type (dot notation)
type BookArray = NonNullable<FunctionReturnType<typeof api.books.queries.list>>
type Book = BookArray[number]

// ✅ GOOD: For slash-separated module paths, extract query function reference first
// TypeScript doesn't support bracket notation for slash-separated module paths
// eslint-disable-next-line @typescript-eslint/no-explicit-any
const editionsQueryRef = (api as any)['bookEditions/queries']['listByBookId']

type EditionArray = NonNullable<FunctionReturnType<typeof editionsQueryRef>>
type Edition = EditionArray[number]

// ❌ BAD: Manually defining types
type Book = {
  _id: Id<'books'>
  title: string
  // ... manually listing all fields - this will get out of sync!
}
```

**Rules:**

- Use `FunctionReturnType<typeof api.module.queries.functionName>` for single return values
- For array returns, first extract the array type, then use `[number]` to get the element type
- Wrap with `NonNullable<>` if the query can return `null` or `undefined`
- For slash-separated module paths (e.g., `bookEditions/queries`), create a helper type alias `type ApiAny = typeof api as any` first, then use `ApiAny['module/queries']['functionName']`
- Always add an eslint-disable comment when using `as any` for slash-separated paths

## Common Patterns

### Upsert Pattern

```typescript
export const upsert = internalMutation({
  args: { asin: v.string(), title: v.string() },
  handler: async (context, args) => {
    const existing = await context.db
      .query('books')
      .withIndex('by_asin', (q) => q.eq('asin', args.asin))
      .unique()

    if (existing) {
      return await context.db.patch(existing._id, { title: args.title })
    }
    return await context.db.insert('books', args)
  },
})
```

### Resolving File URLs

```typescript
const booksWithUrls = await Promise.all(
  books.map(async (book) => {
    const coverUrl = book.coverStorageId ? await context.storage.getUrl(book.coverStorageId) : null
    return { ...book, coverUrl }
  }),
)
```
